abstract = {Tri Doan University of Colorado Colorado Springs E mail: tdoan@uccs.edu Jugal Kalita University of Colorado, Colorado Springs E mail: jkalita@uccs.edu Abstract—Classification is often referred to as the task of discriminating one class from others in a given set of classes. Nonexisting class during training can lead to poor performance of even state-of-the-art classifiers due to unknown classes being incorrectly identified to other classes. An example of an unseen class during training is evolving data when all classes may not be available at training time. Recent development of open set recognition adopts an incremental learning approach due to its natural design to learn unknown objects during its operation. We introduce our Nearest Centroid Class classifier which is able to detect and learn unknown classes incrementally. We experiment our model for document classification on different domains which shows our proposed algorithm yields promising results.},
